HEADWORD: Seggar
<hw>Seg"gar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prov. E.
<ets>saggard</ets> a seggar, <ets>seggard</ets> a sort of riding
surtout, contr. fr. <ets>safeguard</ets>.]</ety> <def>A case or holder
made of fire clay, in which fine pottery is inclosed while baking in the
kin.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>saggar</asp>, <asp>sagger</asp>,
and <asp>segger</asp>.]</altsp> <rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

